<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910111-0049</DOCNO><DOCID>910111-0049.</DOCID><HL>   Who's News   LTV Files Compensation   Plan in Executives' Shift</HL><DATE>01/11/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3</SO><CO>   LTV</CO><IN>STEEL MANUFACTURERS (STL)BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)</IN><LP>   DALLAS -- LTV Corp. plans to pay its new chief executiveofficer a base salary of $550,000, before a performance-basedbonus that could double his pay, court filings show.   The steel, aerospace and defense concern also said itplans to pay Raymond A. Hay, who is to retire as chairman andchief executive, $750,000 a year for consulting services,along with providing him an office, secretarial services anda car. Mr. Hay's contract is to last for about 30 months.</LP><TEXT>   The compensation plans, which must be approved by a NewYork bankruptcy court, follow last week's disclosure thatDavid H. Hoag, head of LTV's steel unit, will succeed Mr.Hay, who has been chairman and chief executive for eightyears. The leadership change is expected to take effect Feb.1.   In 1989, the most recent year for which figures areavailable, Mr. Hay's total compensation was $938,000.   Under LTV's compensation plan, Mr. Hoag could be paid anadditional sum equaling his base salary, depending on howwell he meets certain goals. The filing said his targetcompensation for 1991 under that plan is $275,000, whichwould give him total pay of $825,000.   Mr. Hoag's five-year contract also calls for LTV topurchase annuities for him that would provide $500,000 a yearbeginning at age 60. If he is fired for any reason other thancause, he would receive 150% of his base salary.   A bankruptcy court hearing to consider the executivechanges and compensation is scheduled for next Thursday. LTVhas been operating with protection from creditors underChapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code since 1986.</TEXT></DOC>